This should probably be about `mulSingle`
These match lemmas under the `Finset` namespace. But, well spotted, I had forgotten the `Pi.mulSingle` lemmas.
Can you prove them with the `Finset` lemmas to make that connection clear?
That's prone to regolfing. I've added some "See also" instead (although they look a bit stupid since we're not going to put a docstring on every `Fintype.X` to also see `Finset.X`)

I think a single-lemma proof is more valuable than `by simp`, so I don't buy the regolfing argument. See also in the docstring isn't checked by CI and doesn't link in VSCode. It also means that if someone refactors the `Finset` lemmas, CI reminds them to adjust the `Fintype` ones too.
What about that idea on Zulip to have a tag for lemmas which are not tagged simp because they are provable by simp?
I have reworked the proofs the way you wanted
Can you explain *which* simpNF error this is guarding against?
That the statement can't simplify itself.

I'd lean towards adding an `_iff` here and below
```suggestion
lemma prod_sdiff_eq_prod_sdiff_iff :
```

```suggestion
lemma prod_ite_eq_ite_exists (p : ι → Prop) [DecidablePred p] (h : ∀ i j, p i → p j → i = j) (a : α) :
```
This looks like `Function.update` to me, which would avoid the `ndrec`
This one might be worthy of a docstring
Actually I found a nice lemma to abstract from the proof, but it's not nice not to need this lemma.
Any reason not to match `x ∉ s₁ → f x = 1` from `Finset.prod_subset`?

It's much more useful this way, I find, as it can be interpreted as saying that the support of `f` is a subset of `s`. `Finset.prod_subset` can't really afford to be stated like that as it instead wants to emphasize `s₁ \ s₂`.

```suggestion
#align finset.disj_Union_disj_Union Finset.disjiUnion_disjiUnion

variable [DecidableEq β] {s : Finset α} {t : Finset β} {f : α → β}
```
